========================================================================
                              Editorial
========================================================================
    We have a rather dangerous precident this week.  An network
co-ordinator has been told that publishing an article in
Fidonews is grounds for excommunication.

    When Max and I took over the editorship of the snooze, I
made a personal promise to Tom Jennings to run it according to
his ideals, at least as best as we could.  That did not include
a completely blind adherenec to the "we print what we get"
motto, but close to it.  Grounds for not running an article are
left to the discretion of the editors.  They might include
commercialism, or even triviality, but never simple questioning
of authority.

FidoNews 12-47                 Page:  2                    20 Nov 1995

    Through the last few years, we have run many articles that
have attacked our personal integrity without comment.  We have
published articles in spite of middle of the night harrasment
calls, legal threats, and even, in one case a bomb threat.

    I deeply resent this muzzling of the snooze, and consider it
not only a personal insult, but, if allowed uncontested, a
threat to the existance of fidonet.  I am signing this
editorial, the first one I ever have signed.

Donald L. Tees
